docs.abstract: Somewhere along the way, the superhero publisher lost teenage readers. With new imprints — and writers like Ridley Pearson and Mariko Tamaki — it hopes to change that.
docs.snippet: Somewhere along the way, the superhero publisher lost teenage readers. With new imprints — and writers like Ridley Pearson and Mariko Tamaki — it hopes to change that.
docs.lead_paragraph: DC Entertainment, the home of Batman, Superman, Wonder Woman and a legion of other heroes, is planning two new graphic novel imprints aimed at younger readers. DC Zoom will feature stories for middle school readers, and DC Ink will focus on young adults. Books from the two divisions are scheduled to come out in the fall.

headline.main: DC Comics Joins Forces With Young Adult Authors
headline.print_headline: DC Comics Joining Forces  With Young Adult Authors

docs.abstract: The magazines, some of the most celebrated titles in the industry, clashed with the lifestyle publications favored by Meredith, which bought Time Inc. last year.
docs.snippet: The magazines, some of the most celebrated titles in the industry, clashed with the lifestyle publications favored by Meredith, which bought Time Inc. last year.
docs.lead_paragraph: Since the Meredith Corporation announced its $2.8 billion deal for Time Inc. in November, the company has hinted that it might not hold on to Time magazine, Sports Illustrated, Fortune and Money. Those titles, heavy with news, clashed with the company’s portfolio of lifestyle publications like Better Homes and Gardens, Family Circle and Allrecipes.

headline.main: Meredith Says It Intends to Sell Time, Sports Illustrated, Fortune and Money
headline.print_headline: Meredith Plans to Sell Time And 3 Other Magazines

docs.abstract: A fresh $6.2 billion post-tax charge provides another reason for the conglomerate to consider a breakup. But the value of G.E.’s businesses may make it hard to do.
docs.snippet: A fresh $6.2 billion post-tax charge provides another reason for the conglomerate to consider a breakup. But the value of G.E.’s businesses may make it hard to do.
docs.lead_paragraph: General Electric’s profligate past is haunting its future. A fresh $6.2 billion post-tax charge relating to reinsurance — a business the company left over a decade ago — shows the challenge of managing a conglomerate. As the chief executive John Flannery struggles to reshape the $163 billion company, it’s another reason to consider a breakup.

headline.main: Why Breaking Up General Electric May Be Hard to Do

docs.abstract: The trade representative said steel and aluminum from the European Union and several other exporters might be spared from tariffs about to be imposed.
docs.snippet: The trade representative said steel and aluminum from the European Union and several other exporters might be spared from tariffs about to be imposed.
